text: The Immaculate Conception Catholic Church and Rectory in St. Helena, Nebraska was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2001. The Gothic Revival church was built during 1896–1897. It was designed by architect Josef Schwartz, who also designed the similar-looking Ss. Peter and Paul Catholic Church about away in Bow Valley, Nebraska. The rectory was built in 1919 and is a two-and-a-half-story Four Square house. The town of St. Helena had population of 87 in the 1990 census.
